{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Paolo Uccello 047.jpg | title=Saint George and the Dragon | artist=Paolo Uccello | year=c. 1470 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=55.6 | width_metric=74.2 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[London]] | museum=[[National Gallery, London|National Gallery]] }}
'''''Saint George and the Dragon''''' is a painting by [[Paolo Uccello]] dating from around 1470. It is on display in the [[National Gallery, London]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref>[http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/paintings/paolo-uccello-saint-george-and-the-dragon Paolo Uccelo | Saint George and the Dragon | NG6294], [[The National Gallery, London]].</ref> It was formerly housed in the [[Palais Lanckoroński]] in Vienna, belonging to Count Lanckoroński and sold by his son and heir Anton in 1959 through Mr Farago. The first mention of it being there is 1898.
Gothicizing tendencies in Paolo Uccello's art are nowhere more apparent than in this painting. It shows a scene from the famous story of [[Saint George and the dragon]]. On the right George is spearing the beast, and on the left the princess is using her belt as a leash to take the dragon up to the town.
The eye in the storm gathering on the right of Saint George is lined up with his spear showing there has been divine intervention.
An earlier less dramatic version of the same subject by the Italian artist is in the Musée Jacquemart-André, Paris.
The painting is used as the basis for the [[U. A. Fanthorpe]] poem, ''Not My Best Side'',<ref>{{cite web |url= http://english.emory.edu/classes/paintings&poems/uccello.html|title= Not My Best Side, U.A. Fanthrope|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|publisher= Emory University|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref> and may have served as inspiration for [[John Tenniel|Sir John Tenniel]]'s illustration of the [[Jabberwock]] in ''[[Through the Looking-Glass|Through the Looking-Glass, and What Alice Found There]]''.<ref>Gardner, Martin (1999) ''The Annotated Alice: The Definitive Edition''. W. W. Norton & Co.</ref>
